            "id": "3979fc89164c4f00bde74",
            "questionText": "A satellite is orbiting Earth in an elliptical orbit. At its closest approach (perigee), its distance from Earth's center is $!$r_1 = 7000\\,\\text{km}$!$ and its speed is $!$v_1 = 8000\\,\\text{m/s}$!$. At its farthest point (apogee), its distance from Earth's center is $!$r_2 = 21000\\,\\text{km}$!$. Given that the mass of the satellite is $!$m = 500\\,\\text{kg}$!$, the gravitational constant is $!$G = 6.674 \\times 10^{-11}\\,\\text{N}\\cdot\\text{m}^2/\\text{kg}^2$!$, and the mass of the Earth is $!$M = 5.972 \\times 10^{24}\\,\\text{kg}$!$, calculate the total energy $!$E_T$!$ of the satellite in its orbit.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "8454f1ab42c54a7e984c7",
                    "stepText": "Let's begin by identifying the correct formula for the kinetic energy at perigee. Choose the correct expression that represents the kinetic energy for a moving object.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ea1e89e6-51eb-4c26-9db9-4af747efca26"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$KE = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$KE = mv^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$KE = \\frac{mv}{2}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "1677e89f4cb14b668d7b6",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, using the formula for kinetic energy and the values $!$m = 500\\,\\text{kg}$!$ and $!$v_1 = 8000\\,\\text{m/s}$!$, calculate the kinetic energy at perigee. Remember to convert all units if necessary.",
